questions.question:
Examine the following Python code:

import requests

token = 'Bearer <access_token>'
workspace_id = 'abc-123'
url = f'https://api.fabric.microsoft.com/v1/workspaces/{workspace_id}/git/updateFromGit'

payload = {
    'remoteCommitHash': 'latest',
    'conflictResolution': {'conflictResolutionType': 'Workspace'}
}

headers = {'Authorization': token, 'Content-Type': 'application/json'}
response = requests.post(url, json=payload, headers=headers)

What is the purpose of this API call?

A developer's CI/CD automation script fails authentication. The current header is:

headers = {'Authorization': 'access_token_here'}

They know Fabric REST APIs require proper Bearer token authentication. What is the corrected header?

A developer receives this response from the Fabric Git status REST API:

{
  'changes': [
    {
      'itemMetadata': {'displayName': 'SalesNotebook', 'itemType': 'Notebook'},
      'remoteChange': 'None',
      'workspaceChange': 'Modified'
    },
    {
      'itemMetadata': {'displayName': 'CustomerPipeline', 'itemType': 'DataPipeline'},
      'remoteChange': 'Added',
      'workspaceChange': 'None'
    }
  ]
}

What does this response indicate?
